04974nam a22005775i 9780822386667DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223866677 a10.1515/97808223866672doi  a(DE-B1597)554263  a(OCoLC)1226679360  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHF3400.P68bM36 2005 7aBUS0230002bisacsh1 aMangan, Jane E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTrading Roles :bGender, Ethnicity, and the Urban Economy in Colonial Potosí /cJane E. Mangan; Sonia Saldívar-Hull, Irene Silverblatt, Walter D. Mignolo. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b5 b&w photos, 5 tables, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin America otherwise : languages, empires, nations00tFrontmatter -- tAbout the Series -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 ''The Largest Population and the Most Commerce'': The Genesis of Potosí's Urban Economy -- t2 Making Room to Sell: Location, Regulation, and the Properties of Urban Trade -- t3 Light on the Chicha, Heavy on the Bread: The Colonial Market for Brewing and Baking -- t4 TheWorld of Credit in the City of Silver -- t5 EnterprisingWomen: Female Traders in the Urban Economy -- t6 ¿Vale un Potosí? The Urban Marketplace in the Face of Decline, 1650-1700 -- tConclusions -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLocated in the heart of the Andes, Potosí was arguably the most important urban center in the Western Hemisphere during the colonial era. It was internationally famous for its abundant silver mines and regionally infamous for its labor draft. Set in this context of opulence and oppression associated with the silver trade, Trading Roles emphasizes daily life in the city's streets, markets, and taverns. As Jane E. Mangan shows, food and drink transactions emerged as the most common site of interaction for Potosinos of different ethnic and class backgrounds. Within two decades of Potosí's founding in the 1540s, the majority of the city's inhabitants no longer produced food or alcohol for themselves; they purchased these items. Mangan presents a vibrant social history of colonial Potosí through an investigation of everyday commerce during the city's economic heyday, between the discovery of silver in 1545 and the waning of production in the late seventeenth century.Drawing on wills and dowries, judicial cases, town council records, and royal decrees, Mangan brings alive the bustle of trade in Potosí. She examines "idian economic transactions in light of social custom, ethnicity, and gender, illuminating negotiations over vendor locations, kinship ties that sustained urban trade through the course of silver booms and busts, and credit practices that developed to mitigate the pressures of the market economy. Mangan argues that trade exchanges functioned as sites to negotiate identities within this colonial multiethnic society. Throughout the study, she demonstrates how women and indigenous peoples played essential roles in Potosí's economy through the commercial transactions she describes so vividly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aSex rolexEconomic aspectszBoliviazPotosíxHistoryy16th century. 0aSex rolexEconomic aspectszBoliviazPotosíxHistoryy17th century. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh1 aMignolo, Walter D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaldívar-Hull, Sonia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilverblatt, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter